<body>
  <header>
    <h1>GitHub Contributions Guide</h1>
    <p>Does uploading demo pages count as contributions?</p>
  </header>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="card">
      <h2>What Counts as Contributions ✅</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><span class="yes">Commits to the default branch</span> (main/master)</li>
        <li><span class="yes">Creating GitHub Pages sites</span></li>
        <li><span class="yes">Opening issues</span> (bug reports, feature requests)</li>
        <li><span class="yes">Creating pull requests</span> (even to your own repos)</li>
        <li><span class="yes">Repository creation</span></li>
        <li><span class="yes">Forking repositories</span></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="tip">
        <p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Regular commits spread across days create a stronger contribution graph than many
          commits on a single day.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>What Doesn't Count ❌</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><span class="no">Commits to non-default branches</span> (unless merged)</li>
        <li><span class="no">Wiki edits</span> (though valuable, not shown on graph)</li>
        <li><span class="no">Adding collaborators</span></li>
        <li><span class="no">Starring or watching repositories</span></li>
        <li><span class="no">Comments on issues/PRs</span> (valuable but not commits)</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="tip">
        <p><strong>Note:</strong> Even if an activity doesn't show on your contribution graph, it still adds value to
          your GitHub profile.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>How to Make Your Demo Page Count More</h2>

  <div class="card">
    <ul>
      <li>Use <span class="highlight">GitHub Pages</span> to host your demo - this creates a contribution</li>
      <li>Make regular commits over time rather than one big push</li>
      <li>Create issues to track your progress and future enhancements</li>
      <li>Write good README.md files with documentation</li>
      <li>Use meaningful commit messages that describe your changes</li>
      <li>Create pull requests for new features instead of direct commits</li>
      <li>Add licenses to make your project more professional</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="tip">
    <p><strong>Remember:</strong> While contribution graphs are satisfying, the real value is in creating a portfolio
      that demonstrates your skills to potential employers or collaborators.</p>
  </div>

  <footer>
    <p>GitHub contribution activity is based on commits to the default branch, issues, pull requests, and repository
      creation.</p>
  </footer>
</body>

